The paper proposes a method for detecting white matter injury in preterm neonate brains using magnetic resonance images. This involves detecting ventricles and identifying tissue adjacent to them, and then using outlier intensities to identify potential WMI candidates. The method is segmentation-free, unsupervised, and atlas-free, and is designed to be fast. Given these characteristics, the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the method involves outlier detection and heuristics, which suggests that it may also be relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-categories. The use of normal distribution assumptions and intensity-based analysis suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the use of magnetic resonance images suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
